fields.description:
h3. Issue Summary
When using the Advanced configuration for Confluence, the administrator must create a Classic App in Slack -- see [our standard KB|https://confluence.atlassian.com/slack/use-slack-and-confluence-together-966662503.html#UseSlackandConfluencetogether-IusemultipleConfluenceServerinstancesormyinstancesarebehindafirewall.HowdoIconnectthemtoSlack?].

To create a Classic App in Slack, the administrator must access the following URL: [https://api.slack.com/apps?new_classic_app=1]

The *Go to Slack* button in Confluence doesn't send the administrator to that URL, which may create a standard Slack App, which won't work with Confluence.



h3. Steps to Reproduce
 # Install a vanilla instance of Confluence -- this was validated on Confluence 7.2.1.
 # Install the official [Confluence Server for Slack|https://marketplace.atlassian.com/apps/1220186/confluence-server-for-slack-official?hosting=server&tab=overview] App from the Marketplace -- validated with App version 2.1.0.
 # In Confluence, go to *Cog icon* > *General configuration* > *Slack integration*.
 # Click on *Set up integration*.
 # In _Choose a connection type_, choose *Advanced*.
 # Under _Create a Slack app_, click on *Go to Slack*.

h3. Expected Results
Clicking on the button sends you to the *Create a Slack App (Classic)* form.
 !screenshot-001.png|thumbnail! 

h3. Actual Results
Clicking on the button sends you to the *Create a Slack App* form.
 !screenshot-002.png|thumbnail! 

Continuing on this workflow results in the wrong type of Slack App expected by the Confluence integration.

If the administrator tries the integration with the standard Slack App, the following error will occur on Confluence when trying the integration:
{code}
2020-05-20 17:25:09,796 WARN [http-nio-6734-exec-6] [plugins.slack.util.ResponseMapper] toEither Slack returned an unsuccessful response to oauth.access/<app ID>: oauth_authorization_url_mismatch
 -- url: /c734/rest/slack/latest/oauth | traceId: 3920ce1309d8d89b | userName: admin
{code}


The Confluence App JavaScript has the following URL:
{code}
/* module-key = 'com.atlassian.confluence.plugins.confluence-slack-server-integration-plugin:slack-connect-workspace-resources', location = 'admin/connect/connect-workspace.js' */
goToSlackButton.on('click', function() {
    if (isBasic()) {
        window.open("https://slack.com/apps/" + "AG28M10D8");
    } else {
        var appId = goToSlackButton.data('app-id') || "";
        window.open("https://api.slack.com/apps" + (appId ? "/" + appId : "?new_app=1"));
    }
});
{code}



h3. Workaround
_Currently there is no known workaround for this behavior. A workaround will be added here when available._

Create the Slack App following the documentation and not the information in the UI:
[Use Slack and Confluence together|https://confluence.atlassian.com/slack/use-slack-and-confluence-together-966662503.html#UseSlackandConfluencetogether-IusemultipleConfluenceServerinstancesormyinstancesarebehindafirewall.HowdoIconnectthemtoSlack?]

If the administrator already created the Slack App, it should be deleted and recreated using the documentation mentioned above.

When integrating Confluence and Slack, if a user does not enable/link the Confluence Cloud app when someone shares a Confluence link, the user without the integration/link enabled will see the following message:

{quote}Looks like you've just shared a Confluence Cloud link. To display previews of pages and blog posts from https://instancename.atlassian.net, link your Confluence Cloud site to your Slack account.{quote}

As those users will still need to manually integrate to either see it or stop noticing the message, this is a suggestion to have an option that would allow the app to be integrated for anyone that will be using the Slack application connected to Confluence, instead of needing to manually create the integration, one by one.
